item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
[header style="" type="h3" id="image-hovers"]Image Slider[/header]

With just a few lines of shortcodes (don't worry, it's all done with the help of the visual editor!), you can have the slider below working in no time. It features a thumbnail slider (optional), lightbox integration and a description!

[divider_top text=""] [header style="" type="h3" id="image-hovers"]Basic Usage:[/header] [padding size="5"]

The slider is basically composed of two parts. A wrapping shortcode called "image_slider" where you define your width, height, selector and autoslide time, and multiple children "slide_item" shortcodes, in which you define your slides individually. These are the attributes each shortcode gets:

[column size="one-half"]

"image_slider"

  • width: Width of your slide. Images bigger than this will be cut out (you can use timthumb as well)
    Default: 900
  • height: Height of your slide. Images bigger than this will be cut out (you can use timthumb as well)
    Default: 300
  • selector: Whether or not to show the thumbnails selector.
    Options: true, false — Default: true
  • autoslide: Time in miliseconds for how long to wait in each slide. Don't use to disable it.
    Default: none
[/column] [column size="one-half" last="last"]

"slide_item"

  • title: Title of your slide. Displays at the bottom left.
  • description: Description of your slide. Displays smaller than text at the bottom left.
  • type: Whether to display as lightbox or link upon click.
    Options: lightbox, link — Default: lightbox
  • link: the URL where your slide will lead to upon clicking.
  • width & height: Set width and height to crop the image with timthumb.

item.title: High Beef Prices Could Force Restaurants To Get Creative
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Restaurants are working to keep burgers and sirloins affordable after beef prices hit an all-time high last week and inflation is on the horizon.The price of beef jumped to more than $2.11 per pound for choice-grade beef, breaking a record that had stood since 2003. The inflation is expected to continue and if restaurants don’t want to raise menu prices, other changes will need to be made, according to Nation’s Restaurant News. “It’s not that anything particularly notable has happened in the past month or the past week,” said Richard Volpe, a research economist for the food economics division of the USDA. “We are in a long-term sustained inflation for beef and veal prices.” John Barone, commodities analyst at Market Vision Inc. said the inflation of beef prices is likely to continue through 2016 or possibly 2017. Until the rise in inflation subsides, restaurants will be forced to engineer and market menus with less beef, cheaper cuts and be more vigilant in making the best deals with suppliers, according to NRN.

item.title: $11.7 Million Allocated to Melbourne’s Federation Square Renewal
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: One year after ranking eighth in the London Daily Telegraph’s list of the 21 of the ugliest buildings ever designed and built, Melbourne’s iconic Federation Square is receiving $11.7 million to be upgraded and, hopefully, taken off the “Ugly List.” The Victorian Coalition Government committed money from the 2013-14 state budget to ensure Federation Square is the most popular meeting point in the city both for locals and tourists. “Federation Square is one of the city’s most successful projects. It is home to major cultural attractions, world-class events, tourism experiences and an exceptional array of restaurants, bars and specialty stores,” said Treasurer Michael O’Brien. The Square, capable of holding up to 10,000 people at a time, has hosted countless events, festivals and activities, operating 24 hours a day, seven days a week, for the last 10 years. While it was built in anticipation of four million visits a year, it currently has 10 million visits a year. In addition to the obvious need for expansion, the continued use of the buildings and climate impacts have inevitably led to deterioration. Some infrastructure pieces are also reaching the end of their operational life. According to Innovation, Services and Small Business Minister Louise Asher, continued funding for Federation Square is integral to asset replacement works on the existing buildings, to keep it as one of the city’s main tourist attractions. “We want to keep Federation Square’s operating infrastructure in good shape for the people of Victoria to continue to enjoy, so basic things like heating and cooling systems, IT and the Building Management Systems need to be kept up to date,” she said. As the renewal plan for Fed Square takes shape, the government has launched a public process seeking ideas for the development of Federation Square East. That site is delimited by Federation Square to the west, Flinders Street to the north, the Exhibition Street Extension to the east and Birrarung Marr to the south, with the majority of the site currently located on the decommissioned Jolimont rail yards. Major Projects Minister David Hodgett announced the search is on for international ideas to transform this “black hole” into a mixed use precinct with a focus on civic functionality and improved connections with its surrounding areas. “The Coalition Government is looking to harness the innovation and creativity of the private sector for proposals to develop this important site,” he said. The goal of the search is to examine the possibilities for the site and how much interest there is in developing it. There are currently no plans to proceed beyond the idea generation stage, as responses to the search will determine whether there is any project viable enough to continue.

[header style="" type="h3"]Some info before you go on[/header]

The column template is based on percentages. Meaning that no matter where you put a one-half column, it will always be half of that total width.

Take some time to read these 4 blocks of information.

[padding size="15"] [column size="one-fourth"] [header style="" type="h3"]Size[/header]

item.title: Viceroy Anguilla
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
It's jaw-droppingly impressive, and it's bringing a new level of luxurious modernity to Anguilla. The crisp white lines and Kelly Wearstler's hyperdesigned interiors may not be your cuppa, but you can't deny the property's 'wow' factor. The Viceroy delivers what it promises. And what it promises is a lifestyle immersion in 21st-century high chic. From afar, the 35-acre resort, which opened in December 2009, looks like a small city landed on the promontory between Meads Bay and Barnes Bay.
The architecture comes into focus up close, the sleek white structures smartly juxtaposed against the blue Anguillan sea and sky -- the layout has good feng shui. Rooms and suites are outfitted with every 21st-century toy, furnished in a palette of cream, sand, and brown punctuated with golden sunbursts (the Viceroy logo). Every suite (except for the Viceroy King) has its own plunge pool; six 'rooftop' suites are duplexes with the plunge pool situated on the second-story terrace, with dizzying sea views. The four- and five-bedroom villas are luxe dialed to 11 -- in the parlance of one very astute fellow, they're 'sick.' Each villa -- more like an exquisite mini-mansion, really -- comes with a ridiculously fabulous kitchen, master baths with deep-soaking tubs and outdoor showers, a pool and outdoor cabana, grill, and hot tub.
Coba, the main restaurant, is encased in glass for seamless sea and sky views. The Sunset Bar feels like the heart of the resort, but an entire second, self-contained family-friendly section has at its center a sprawling pool and restaurant, Aleta. I love the Viceroy's community spirit: Its employee base is 90% Anguillan. One minor issue: The beach around the resort has had some erosion from storms (it's expected to build up again); the best beach is a short walk (or shuttle) away on Meads Bay, where the Viceroy lounges and umbrellas have been set up. The Viceroy is open year-round. Less Most helpful
